    <h3>1.	Game Strategies</h3>
    To recap, a strategy is an approach or algorithm for playing the game.  It defers from a specific move, which is an action taken during a player’s turn. 
    A strategy is usually determined by the payoff, which can change based on the opponent’s strategy.  Most simple games will have a finite number of strategies; 
    this is referred to as a strategy set.  Being aware of the <b>strategy set</b> allows a player to better predict the opponent play, and better utilize matching or 
    opposing strategies to achieve a desired outcome.

    <p></p>A <b>pure strategy</b> is one in which a player selects a strategy to select a single type of action. For example a player choosing to always play rock in rock-paper-scissors would be a pure strategy. 
    
    <p></p>A <b>mixed strategy</b> is an assignment of probabilities for all choices in the strategy set.  The strategy set for rock-paper-scissors contains: 
    <i>S = {Always-Rock, Always-Paper, Always-Scissors}</i>, then the probability distribution would be 33.33% for this mixed strategy.
    
</div>

<div id="divSection2" style="display:none" class="div-tutorial">
    <h3>2.	Prisoner’s Dilemma Strategy</h3>

    <p></p>In the normal-form prisoner’s dilemma where each player is separated and has a single simultaneous choice, the strategy would be to identify the dominant 
    pure strategy.  Since there is no danger of the opponent penalizing our decision on a subsequent turn, a dominant strategy (when a player will play the best 
    strategy regardless of the opponent’s choices) will be the best one.

    <p></p><img src="/images/matrix2.png" width="400px"/>

    <p></p>To arrive at the dominant strategy, we will tabulate the payoff totals for each choice:
    <ul>
        <li>Staying silent can receive -1 or -3 = -4 Total</li>
        <li>Confessing can receive 0 or -2 = -2 Total</li>
    </ul>    
    
    

    Since we do not know how the opponent will select, confessing against your opponent would be the dominant strategy regardless of how the opponent chooses. 
    However, the opponent knowing the dominant strategy for the game would also choose a dominant strategy of confessing, making it likely the outcome of the 
    game would be A, B = (-2, -2).  This is the Nash Equilibrium for this scenario.
</div>

