    <h3>4.	Iterated Sequential Prisoner’s Dilemma Strategy</h3>
    In an iterated sequential prisoner’s dilemma game, both players are able to penalize or reward the other for their cooperation or betrayal on the previous turn. 
    What types of strategy would be optimal in this type of game?

    <p></p><img src="/images/matrix3.png" width="400px"/>
    
    <p></p>Let us examine some common strategies available for an iterated sequential game:
    <ol>
        <li><b>Always cooperate</b>: will choose a pure-strategy of always cooperate</li>
        <li><b>Always betray</b>: will choose a pure-strategy of always betray</li>
        <li><b>Tit-for-Tat</b>: will begin with cooperate, and continues to copy your last move</li>
        <li><b>Grudger</b>: will begin with cooperate and continue cooperating, until they are betrayed against at which point they will always betray</li>
        <li><b>Hard Majority</b>: will begin with betray, and continues to betray as long as the number of times the opponent has betrayed is equal or greater 
            than the number of times it has cooperated; otherwise it cooperates</li>
    </ol>
        
    There are many more variations of strategies, including the Southampton group strategy developed by England’s Southampton University which has which won 
    the 20th anniversary iterated prisoner’s dilemma competition.
    

</div>

