                <p></p>But there are some basics lessons which can be gleaned from this exercise:
                <ul>
                    <li><b>Don’t judge a book by its cover</b>: Repeated interactions produce a better picture of how people will behave. Many of the game strategies started with an initial cooperate or defect to probe, but changed in response to the opponent strategy revealing its true nature.</li>
                    <li><b>Play nicely with others</b>: look for opportunities to cooperate when others are willing for a mutually beneficial experience. The strategies which rewarded good behaviour had much higher payoff outcome</li>
                    <li><b>Forgive and forget</b>: it is natural for people to make mistakes, so be willing to forgive their mistakes and trust again. The tit-for-tat is a successful strategy because it is quickly willing to forgive betrayal</li>
